Case Study Scenario

In many spatial analysis roles, GISers find themselves repeating processes on a regular basis - often for formal/annual reports.

In Lab 3-1, you learned different concepts in remote sensing and explored two types of spatial analysis that can be done with remotely sensed data: NDVI and NBR. You are working on a multi-year study of how burned area recovers after a fire. You will recreate the process from Lab 3-1 using both ModelBuilder (drag and drop style window and tools) and ArcPy, a python package specifically for working geospatially, which stores python code for each of the geoprocessing tools we commonly use.

Geoprocessing tools (used in lab 3-1), ModelBuilder, and ArcPy/Python all accomplish the same task, through different approaches.Doing analysis through standalone tools (Geoprocessing) is a great way to undertake initial data exploration, but would have to be redone each time. Using ModelBuilder or ArcPy allows for not only repeating processes on a regular basis, but also for visualizing workflows as well as easily sharing processes with others.

Part 1a: ModelBuilder Basics

ModelBuilder uses a “drag and drop” approach to building a replicable workflow. Each tool you drag and drop into the workspace is the same as if you were to run a standalone geoprocess.

The strength of ModelBuilder extends beyond ArcGIS Pro’s classic geoprocessing abilities to emphasize visualization of the workflow. We see how a process is going to run.

Answer: Why might it be beneficial to have a workflow visualization? Who, specifically, may benefit from a workflow visualization?

Per Esri [1] - “ModelBuilder is a visual programming language for building geoprocessing workflows. Geoprocessing models automate and document your spatial analysis and data management processes. You create and modify geoprocessing models in ModelBuilder, where a model is represented as a diagram that chains together sequences of processes and geoprocessing tools, using the output of one process as the input to another process.

ModelBuilder in ArcGIS Pro allows you to do the following:

- Build a model by adding and connecting data and tools.
- Iteratively process every feature class, raster, file, or table in a workspace.
- Visualize your workflow sequence as an easy-to-understand diagram.
- Run a model step by step, up to a selected step, or run the entire model.
- Make your model into a geoprocessing tool that can be shared or can be used in Python scripting and other models.”

Part 1b: ArcPy/Python Basics

If you’re new to Python or coding, you’ve got this!

If you’re a Python pro and would like additional challenges, check out our FREE Esri trainings specific to Python…https://www.esri.com/training/catalog/search/ Search for “python” or “scripting.” You have access to these as long as you have an active UCM Email!

Per Esri - “ArcPy is a Python site package that provides a useful and productive way to perform geographic data analysis, data conversion, data management, and map automation with Python.

This package provides a rich and native Python experience offering code completion (type a keyword and a dot to get a pop-up list of properties and methods supported by that keyword; select one to insert it) and reference documentation for each function, module, and class.

The additional power of using ArcPy is that Python is a general-purpose programming language. It is interpreted and dynamically typed and is suited for interactive work and quick prototyping of one-off programs known as scripts while being powerful enough to write large applications in. ArcGIS applications written with ArcPy benefit from the development of additional modules in numerous niches of Python by GIS professionals and programmers from many different disciplines.”

Behind every geoprocessing tool we run (Yes, the same ones in the Geoprocessing pane and that we used in ModelBuilder) is a snippet of code.

If you need help with Python syntax (aka code wording and arrangement), the Help page for every tool has a Python section that breaks it all down!

Access this page about Clip and scroll to the bottom Parameters section. There will be a table with a Python tab with the code AND an example! https://pro.arcgis.com/en/pro-app/2.8/tool-reference/analysis/clip.htm

Part 2a: ModelBuilder Warm Up

When using ModelBuilder, you work in a separate window, external to our normal map window

  1. Click on the Analysis Ribbon, and open ModelBuilder.

Figure 1: ModelBuilder Ribbon

  1. Mentally note the location of the following buttons. These are basic steps you’ll use regularly if working in ModelBuilder.
  • Tools
  • Group
  • AutoFit
  • Validate
  1. From the Catalog Pane, drag and drop CARiversAndCreeksPRJ and MariposaCountyBoundary feature classes into the Model 1 ModelBuilder window. Click the Auto Layout button to tidy the frame.

Figure 2: ModelBuilder with Two Feature Classes Added

  1. Click on the Tools button in the ModelBuilder Ribbon. This will open our regular Geoprocessing pane. Search for Clip, then drag and drop it into the ModelBuilder frame to the right of your existing inputs.

  2. Connect our inputs to the Clip tool (2 approaches). Try both.

  • You can click and drag each layer one at a time to connect them to Clip.
  • You can double click on Clip to open the dialogue box.

For the approach of your choice, set your Input Features to CARiversAndCreeksPRJ and your Clip Feautures to MariposaCountyBoundary.

  1. Name your output MariposaCountyRiversAndCreeks and click Ok.

  2. Notice how the boxes turned from grey to color? This confirms you have your criteria set (NOTE: It doesnt mean they’re correct, just that it is ready to run). To confirm it has the criteria needed to run, click validate. When we validate, it is a more robust approach to confirming our model has the required settings applied. It does NOT mean, however, human error didn’t occur. These are just extra ways to minimize (but not wholly eliminate) potential for issues.

Figure 3: Prepared Model

  1. Click Run. Upon completion, refresh your geodatabase. You should have a MariposaCountyRiversAndCreeks feature class. Drag and drop the feature class into your Map Window for visual confirmation. You will use this layer later in a production quality map. If you haven’t saved in a while, save now!

Part 2a-1: Replicability and Updates/Editing

One major benefit of using ModelBuilder is that you can save your Model and rerun it at other times, AND even edit it if you need to after it’s been saved. Right click on your RiverClipMod in your Project Toolbox and click Edit. Edit the output name to YourName_ModEdit. Rerun the Model to generate the renamed output.

Part 2b: ArcPy Warm Up

In your same ArcGIS Pro project, access the Analysis Ribbon. In the top left, click the drop-down next to Python and select Python Window.

  1. Call in (type and hit enter) our arcpy package by typing

    import arcpy

  2. Set your Workspace - by doing this, we can streamline coding, as Python knows where data is coming from and going to.

    We want to set our default geodatabase as our workspace.HINT: Drag and drop your GDB in the Catalog pane into the Python window. It will ensure proper syntax. (remember we’re still working in 3-1’s project) Type

    arcpy.env.workspace = your workspace

    into the window and hit enter.

Setting the Workspace

Like with the ModelBuilder Warm Up, we are going to use Clip.

  1. We now want to set our criteria. Type in the following, hitting enter between each line.

in_features = “CARiversAndCreeksPRJ”

clip_features = “MariposaCountyBoundary”

out_feature_class = “MarCoRiversAndCreeks_PY”

You just told it to set your input later to CA Rivers and Creeks, your clip feature (the cookie cutter) to Mariposa County Boundaries, and to name the output MarCoRiversAndCreeksPY.

Now call in the tool by entering…

arcpy.Clip_analysis(in_features, clip_features, out_feature_class)

Congrats! You coded using ArcPy! Drag and drop MarCoRiversAndCreeks_PY from Catalog to your Map window to view the resulting layer.

Python code is also shareable! AND you can set computers to run codes at certain times - e.g. Every Friday night at 10pm. If you worked at an agency, this would be done in collaboration with IT.

Enter the following lines of code into the Python window.

import arcpy arcpy.env.workspace = Your gdb path string = Hello World.

After entering the code and running it, right click on the code and Save Transcript. Save to the desktop for quick/easy access. Name it something relevant to the assignment.

Your lab received a multi-million dollar grant from the USGS to understand how burn risk changes on a landscape after a megafire. This is a longitudinal study, meaning it will be repeated over an extended period (the term longitudinal is not referring to lat/long).

You successfully completed your first attempt at calculating Zonal Statistics previously, and now you are confident that it is the same process you’ll want to run every three months over the next five years. It sounds repetitive and time-wasting to rerun the process from scratch every few months, so you decide to use ModelBuilder.

As a bonus, your non-GISer boss will appreciate seeing the workflow visually, AND the graphics will look great in your annual reports to the USGS.

NBR Process
Your interns (aka you last week) created NBR rasters for July and October.

  1. Drag and drop tm_1707_nbr and tm_1710_nbr into a new ModelBuilder window.
  2. First you need to recalculate the difference, so drag and drop in Raster Calculator from your toolbox into ModelBuilder.
  3. Click and drag to connect tm_1707_nbr and tm_1710_nbr to Raster Calculator, then double click to open the tool.
  4. Build your expression in Raster Calculator, subtracting tm_1710_nbr from tm_1707_nbr. Save the output as DiffNBR_ModBuild. RUN.
  5. Clip DiffNBR_ModBuild to the Detwiler fire boundaries, DetwilerBounds. Name the output ClippedDiffNBR
  6. RUN

    This is a good check in point to ensure the processes are running as anticipated. Check your geodatabase - refresh if needed, and confirm that ClippedDiffNBR is present. Drag and drop ClippedDiffNBR to your map frame for a visual check.

  7. Drag and drop in the Reclassify tool. Set ClippedDiffNBR as the input, and double click on the Reclassify tool to open the dialogue window. Set your classifications to match those from Lab 3-1, as shown below.

Table: Classifications

  1. Name your output tm_Dnbr_cls_Modbuild and click Run. Then, at the top, click Run. The Model should run successfully.

  2. Draw a box around these inputs and Group them using the corresponding tool in the Ribbon. Name the group Classified NBR.

Part 4: ArcPy with Increased Complexity

Right click on the text anywhere in the Python window and Clear Transcript

NBR Process
It is critical to note that Raster Calculator is not designed for use in ArcPy/Python https://desktop.arcgis.com/en/arcmap/10.3/tools/spatial-analyst-toolbox/raster-calculator.htm

We will use previous outputs we created within the Raster Calculator geoprocessing tool to Classify our NBR differential data layer we created in ModelBuilder ClippedDiffNBR

Parent Syntax
https://pro.arcgis.com/en/pro-app/2.8/tool-reference/spatial-analyst/reclassify.htm

Reclassify(in_raster, reclass_field, remap, {missing_values})

Import your arcpy package and set your workspace.

import arcpy

arcpy.env.workspace =“your gdb path”

Enter the following code, one line at a time to set our local variables

in_raster= “DiffNBR_ModBuild”

reclass_field = VALUE

remap=RemapRange([[-0.727323,-0.500000, 1], [-0.500000, -0.250000, 2],etc…) to match remap table from ModelBuilder)

The final step is to name the function you are using so it will create a correspondingly-named output. (i.e. your output raster will be named reclass_NBR.)

reclass_NBR= arcpy.sa.Reclassify(your local variables)

Run the code.

Upon completion, a new layer will be output to your Map window and your geodatabase.
